n the same conflict zone the project will identify common patterns of organizational evolution as groups form split merge collaborate compete shift ideological direction adopt or renounce terrorism grow shrink and eventually decline over time models based on comparisons of historical terrorist genealogies will be applied to the case of al qaeda and its affiliates and associates including the taliban in afghanistan and pakistan theories generated from the study will thus shed light on an important national security threat that is constantly evolving the project will also identify or develop computer software to assemble organize and display information about organizations and their interactions over time this award was funded through the social and behavioral dimensions of national security conflict and cooperation competition a joint venture between nsf and the department of defense downloads pdf+ project plan modified october 2010 pdf mapping_terrorist_organization pdf 1.5 mb contact martha crenshaw funding provided by national science foundation dod's minerva initiative publications cover trajectories of terrorism attack patterns of foreign groups that have targeted the united states 1970 2004 martha crenshaw gary lafree sue ming yang criminology & public policy vol 8 3 2009 pdf+ events & presentations the genealogy of terrorism october 14 2010 cisac research seminar martha crenshaw pdf+ word doc+ paper flyer available mapping terrorist organizations october 8 2009 cisac research seminar martha crenshaw audio+ audio transcript available pdf+ paper available spies and terrorists subversive networks across ideologies and times april 30 2009 cisac social science seminar katya drozdova martha crenshaw pdf+ 3 papers available search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages research news interactive website tracing terrorist family trees to be launched june 17 2010 cisac news martha crenshaw awarded $50